•Panel data of units sold, sales price, base price for 28 products in 76 stores over
1061 days (2 years, 10 months, 26 days, or 34 months 26 days, or 151 weeks 4 days
(including end date) from 8th Jan 2011 to 3rd Dec 2013); includes whether product
is a ‘featured’ product or product on prominent display – dims: (150150 row x 9col)
•Convert to multivariate time series, binning 1 value for each product variable (1 per
product for each of 5 metrics) per timestamp → notebook 1
•140 variables created for multivariate time series over 152 weekly timestamps
(beginning on a ‘Monday’; 10th Jan 2011 to 2nd Dec 2013) → forecast horizon for 19
weeks ahead using Time Series Regression

•Binning: median for metrics units sold, base price, sales price (robust to outliers)
•can't use mode or median for whether product featured or on display as:
oinstances of either can be too infrequent to detect the existing featuring or
displaying in this way
in binning multiple retailings of an individual product in all the different
stores per timestamp
ouse mean as (is_featured count / all product observations) per timestamp,
(is_display count / all product observations) per timestamp
•Measure of how much featuring a product/displaying it was emphasised at that
timestamp → metrics percent_featured, percent_display

Problem and implemented solution Methods used Results Conclusions on solution implementation Bibliography Acknowledgements Extras of interest
•Finding periodicity of time series variables using matrixprofile-ts Python
package (matrixProfile.stomp(), motifs.motifs())–reproducible, automated
measurement of seasonal period
•Adapting software from MIT-licensed Manu Joseph project (2):
Fourier-based multi-seasonal decomposition (justification in notebook 4)
Seasonal imputation for seasonal variables
Outlier detection and treatment using IQR and iForest (seasonal/non-
seasonal; justification: notebook 5)
Baseline forecasting using darts.metrics and darts.models (Theta, FFT;
justification for these models in notebook 6)
Methods used
4
Problem and implemented solution Methods used Results Conclusions on solution implementation Bibliography Acknowledgements Extras of interest
Forecastability assessment for continuous variables by C.o.V., Residual
Variability (for seasonal variables), Spectral Entropy (on residuals for seasonal
variables), Kaboudan Metric/Modified Kaboudan Metric (see notebook 7 for
more)
Train –validation –test set approach to allow performance of model to be
hyperparameter-tuned (justification: notebooks 6, 11)
Time Series Regression using both linear and non-linear approaches (Linear
Regression, Lasso Regression, Linear SVR, XGBoost, LightGBM, Decision Tree,
Random Forest), by ‘Direct’ Strategy (DS) (DS justification: notebook 8)
Evaluation: metrics for continuous outputs (3) (MAE, MSE, MASE, Forecast
Bias); implementation: Best Fit combined forecast

Results
7
Problem and implemented solution Methods used Results Conclusions on solution implementation Bibliography Acknowledgements Extras of interest
•For this time series data ‘Best Fit’ Strategy using Decision Tree model and
(max_depth = 3, min_impurity_decrease = 0.0, min_samples_split = 2)
performs similarly on test set to Best Model on validation set, but slightly worse
•Best Fit combined forecast (using Decision Tree model) on all error metrics
(MAE, MSE, MASE, Forecast Bias) → 0; see prediction match in slide 6 graphs –
Success!
